ance Commitments, Timing, and Quantitative Targets\nThe text outlines several specific quantitative targets, timelines, and performance commitments across its aerospace and AI segments, alongside the financial risks associated with meeting them:\n\n**Aerospace & Connectivity Targets:**\n*   **Launch Cadence:** Accelerating cycle time to launch **over 100 times per year** (noted as a unique industry achievement).\n*   **Network Latency:** Defining a "low-latency network" as **below 70 milliseconds**.\n*   **Constellation Scale:** A "large-scale LEO broadband satellite constellation" is defined as a network of **over 1,000** satellites.\n*   **Artemis Program:** NASA\'s timeline aimed at landing humans on the Moon by the **late 2020s**.\n\n**AI & Compute Timelines/Targets:**\n*   **xAI Acquisition:** The AI business was acquired in **February 2026**.\n*   **Grok\'s Performance Timeline:** Achieved frontier-level scientific reasoning (GPQA Diamond score) **within two years** of its initial model release, outpacing competitors.\n*   **Power vs. Compute Gap (2025):** U.S. compute demand is estimated at **62 gigawatts** in 2025, exceeding the available power generation of **49 gigawatts**.\n*   **Global Infrastructure Investment:** **$7 trillion** in global data center investment is required through **2030**.\n*   **AI Power Demand:** Generative AI workloads are expected to account for roughly **70%** of total data-center power demand by the **end of the decade**.\n\n**Contractual Commitments & Execution Risks:**\n*   **Cost-to-Cost Contract Sensitivities:** The company uses significant management judgment for Space and Connectivity contracts recognized over time. A sensitivity analysis notes that a **1% change** in combined gross margins for these contracts during **2025** would directly impact reported revenue and operating income.\n*   **Risk of Missing Commitments:** The preamble explicitly warns that scaling novel AI and orbital infrastructure involves high risks reg