ortages at SpaceX. By mirroring the in-house manufacturing model used for Starship (where ~80% is built internally), the company expects "significant speed and cost advantages" and a reduction in overall compute costs.\n*   **Complementary Sourcing:** The company explicitly notes that Terafab will *not* entirely replace external suppliers; they will continue sourcing a "significant portion" of compute hardware from third parties, viewing Terafab as a complementary asset to augment access at a massive scale.\n\n### **4. Timing, Status, and Partnerships**\n*   **Partnership Timeline:** The collaboration with Tesla was announced in **March 2026**, and Intel officially joined the project in **April 2026** to contribute its expertise in designing, fabricating, and packaging ultra-high-performance chips.\n*   **Current Development Status:** Currently, the company has only agreed with Tesla on a **"general framework"** for the future development of Terafab. \n*   **Lack of Definitive Timelines:** The filing explicitly states that *"any specific projects undertaken pursuant to this framework will be subject to separate negotiations and agreements (including any development timelines, milestones and capital expenditures) and have not yet been determined."*\n\n### **5. Risk Factor Disclosures**\nThe preamble\'s risk factors highlight significant uncertainties regarding Terafab\'s execution:\n*   **No Binding Obligations:** While a framework agreement exists, **"neither Tesla nor Intel are obligated to remain a part of the project,"** and the company may never enter into definitive, binding agreements with them.\n*   **Execution Risk:** There is *"no assurance that we will be able to achieve our objectives with respect to Terafab within the expected timeframes, or at all."*\n*   **Supply Chain Vulnerability:** If Terafab faces delays or fails to materialize, the company warns it *"may not have other sources of sufficient AI chips to meet our orbital AI compute demands,"* leavi