s."\n* **Rapid Iteration:** The text highlights extreme vertical integration (producing the "tools that make the tools") as a mechanism "enabling us to test, fail, and iterate rapidly" and release "newer, more advanced hardware."\n* **The Factory as the Product:** "We view our factories as the machines that build the machines and maintain a relentless focus on our ability to move..."\n\n### 3. Planning vs. Execution: "The Algorithm"\nRather than relying on traditional, static corporate planning, the company utilizes a rigid, five-step execution framework known internally as **"The Algorithm"** to govern day-to-day operations and engineering:\n* **The 5-Step Iterative Process:** "We operate under a set of core execution principles that we refer to as \'The Algorithm\'... make less dumb, delete, optimize, accelerate, automate."\n* **Step 1 (Question Requirements):** "We make the requirements less dumb..."\n* **Step 2 (Delete):** "...delete unnecessary processes or parts (embracing the principle that **the best part is no part**)..."\n* **Step 3 (Optimize):** "...only then optimize the necessary processes or parts..."\n* **Step 4 (Accelerate):** "...and then accelerate cycle time (many entities have launched once; no one other than us has ever launched over 100 times per year)..."\n* **Step 5 (Automate):** "...and automate only proven processes after the first four steps are completed."\n\n### Summary of the Strategic Mindset\nIn this prospectus, **planning** is framed not as a fixed roadmap, but as a continuous, aggressive loop of questioning requirements and deleting waste. **Execution** is defined by extreme speed, vertical integration (described as a "shovels-to-tokens" approach for AI), and a willingness to break things early to gather empirical data. Ultimately, the company views its execution capability as a "self-reinforcing cycle" where success in one domain (like launch cadence) fuels rapid iteration and capital reinvestment into the next frontier (like orbital AI compute).',
